{"/service/ndnp/tu/batch_tu_dinah_ver01/data/sn98069867/00415621723/1920121701/1194.xml":{"full_text":"FRIDAY, DECEMBER 17, 138.\nTHE NEWS SCIMITAR.\nPAGE THREE.\nV'\nT\nMANY REDUCTIONS\n6ere U aome good news for th inti\nmate consumer, .provided toe can, get\nbis retailer t pass it on to him.\nThe past day, or so has brought a\nconsiderable decline In the prices of a\nnumber of staple food articles, par\nticularly In packing house products. Thf\ndeclinea are expeeted to be followed\n1 by others, tinless there' is a change in\ncertain conditions and indications. They\nhave not been as surprising to the Veil\ninformed as might be expecte, al\nthough the start was a. bit slow. T\nContributing largely to', the rapidity\nof the declines, once they got started,\nis the vgive of economy which has ac\ncompanied the aeneral business reac\ntion. Unusually mild weather has been\nanother factor, while the \"buyers\nBtrike\" is admittedly quite prominent.\nBat another factor is that the produc\ntion in the United States bas been tare-\ner than anticipated, with less outlet to\nother countries than many thought\nprobable.\nKkbs. which are still about the' hlrh\nest item in staple foods, have toppled\nseveral cents a dozen and on iYtday\nwere selling from the wholesaler at 71\nto 75 cents a dozen by the case for\nbest quality fresh. ImNew York, the\nchief market of the country, prices have\ndropped sharply, with the chief excuse\norrered warm weather and larger pro\nduction. Stot-age. eggs are belns; sold\nhere at 65 cents ft dozen and less.\nCheese has toppled and best grade\nor cream is joDDinc here at to\ncents a pound,, with the market u\nsettled.\nCreamery butter is plentiful and sell\ning around 48 to 60 cents for best\nquality.\nTurning to meats, there Is much un\nsettlement in the market, with pure\nhog lard moving at 16 to 16 cents a\npound, a dron of five or, six cents with\nin a week, while compound variety\nis selling at ,12 to cents. Dry\nsalt meat is selling at 15V4 to ltt\ncents a pound, while besf grade of\nhams are to be had at 25 to 28 cents\na pound and picnics at 18 to 20. Best\ngrade breakfast bacon is quoted at 42\nto 44 cents, with what are known as\nv seconds at 30. t\nFresh meats are not so unsettled as\nthe cured, although declines In such\nhave been under way for Some time.\nIn groceries there is not so much\nchange, although refined sugar is to be\nhad at 0 cents a pound and less at the\ncash retail store, with rice around 6\ncents. Cornmeal is selling from the\nJobber at J 2. 20 for 100-pound sacks, with\nMlour rather slow to respond, still be-\nIn minted at 110 tn 112 a. barrel.\nIn vegetables prices are reasonable, i\ninah poratoea are flemng irom the joo\nber at $2 to $2.20 a hundred and onions\nabout the same, uabbafte is going at\nlean than 2 cents a ooundr Fancy\nvegetables continue rather high, but one\nof the chief reasons is that 'freight\nand express rates are so1 high and re\nceipts are coming in small shipments.\nFruits are not showing milch change,\nbut oranges are quotable anywhere,\nfrom $3.50 to (4.50 a box, while apples\nare selling at' $5 to $8 for best fruits\nin barrels.\nDECLINES TO DEBATE.\nCHARLESTON, W. Va., Ded. 17.-.\nJov. Cornwall declined the Invita\ntion issued by Socialist party leaders\nin New York-that he enter Into a\ndebate with Seymour Stedman on\nthe subject of conditions in the West\nVirginia mining fields. The gover\nnor gave three reasons tor declining,\nnamely, that he is not opposed to\nunion labor or collective bargaining;\nthat he would be too busy with leg\nIslative matters in the Immediate fu\nture and that he Is not in favor of\nunionizing nonunion fields by force.\nMRS. CULVER LAYS\nVirginia Beach Woman Freed\nof Rheumatism and Stom-\n'ach Trouble.by Tanlac Says\nAll Her Troubles Are Gone.\n\"I've laid my old crutches awav.\nfor I don't need them any more since\nI took Tanlac,\" said -Mrs. B. C. Cul\nver, of Virginia Beach, Va. i\n\"About a year ago I lost my ap\npetite and my stomach got In such\na bad condition I couldn't eat any\nthing without suffering terrible\npains. I had to glvA up coffee, fruits\nand vegetables because they hurt\nme so much. My liver got out of\norder. I always had an awful bad\ntaste in my'mouth and at times got\nso dizzy I could hardly stand. I got\nso:: weak I couldn't do my housed\nwork and finally begai having rheu\nmatism in my feet and ankles so I\nCouldn't walk vUtHout crutches. I\nwas so nervous I couldn't sleep well,\narid every llay I seemed to feel more\ntired and worn out than the day\nbefore. 1\n\"One day some, friends told me\nsliow Tanlac, had helped them and\nbefc-ged me to try 4t. Well, r got\neight bottles and before I had fin\nished the first two I was eating any\nthing I wanted, even fruits And\nvegetables, without suffering, and\nwhen T had finished my third bottle\nthe. rheumatlm was gone and I had\nlaid my crutches away. All my trou\nbles are gone now, my nerves are\nperfectly calm and 1 sleep like a\nchild every flight.\"\nTanjac is sold by the ading drug\ngists in every tow if. adv.\nFor Qhri&tmas\nMake the world look bel-\n\"ter to someoneby giving\nfhat someone a pair of\ninodern glasses. Easjly'\narranged if you see ua.\ni\nJ. Jce Marsh\nH W. Liggette\nLIGGETTE\nOPTICAL\ni CO.\n108 Madison 'Avenue\nLiggette Optical Service\nin Memphis Thirty Years\nCRUTCHES\nWives Aid Men In\nFight With Bandits\nIn Big N.Y: Hotel\n(By International News Service.)\nv NEW YORK, tc. 'r it Police\nhoped todayto round up two bandit\n\"pals\" of Lawrence Handlboe, 22, of\nRichmond, Va., who helped, him\nstage ,the most sensational holdup\nin weeks by invading the rooms of\ntwo men and their wives 'at the\nHotel Astor. 1 j,\nAlthough covered by'1 revolvers\nOwen CT Linthwalte anq H L. ,Wor\nley, New Jersey suburbanites, began\nto battle tne robbers.\" Mrs. Llnth\nwaite and Mrs. Worley assisted their\nhusbands in the fight which raged\nfor half an hour, wrecking the room.\nNot until Mrs. Linthwalte' broke a\nwindow on the second floor, was at\ntention attracted to the melee.\nWhen police arrived they found\nthe four guests sitting on Handlboe,\nwho had been knocked unconscious.\nIn his pockets police said were rings'\nand bracelets snatched from the wo\n\"men. The two thugs who escaped\nhad managed to snatch 492 from\nLinthwalte' s 'pocket.\nThe women \"were suffering- today\nfrom kicks and blows delivered by\nthe robberl. Their frocks were torn\nIn the struggle to aid -their husi\nbandtj.\nEPIDEMIC PUZZLES.\nWASHINGTON Dec,, ,fl-r-An epi\ndemic, which American naval doctors\nhave diagnosed as smallpox but which\nother medical authorities believe to be\nkafir pox, prevails in Jamaica. Latest\nreports to the public health service in\ndicate that there were 330 cases of the\ndisease. No quarantine has been im\nposed. Haitians have claimed that the\npresent epidemic of smallpox on their\nislands reached there from Jamaica.\nThe Public Is (jordially Invited to Hear a Free\nLecture, On.\nChristian Science\nBy lleV. Andrew J. Graham, C.S.B.\nI \"v of Boston, Mass.\n\nMember of The' Board of Lectureship of The Mother Church,\nV The' First Churqh of Christ, Scientist,\nin Boston Massachusetts.\nChurch Edifice, Dunlap\nv Jtoday, December 17,\nHEY! You\nXmas Shoppers\n\nLadies Especially\nWe want to call your attention to,\nPeiser's Sale of Men's IirnishV:\nings. If it's a gift for a man a\nreal HE MAN we have it--ahd\nour price's will, save you a lot of\nmoney on your purchases.\ni\nHatJ ShirU Underwear\n4 IiOnnjring Robes Sox Ties\nAll Radically Reduced.\nHirshWickWire Ready-for-Service Suits\nless than cost $34.75-$49.75. yr\nSee our display of tailoring patterns that\nwe of ferXat $60.00.\n\"if\n42 South\nA Chid's\nThe best Christmas present for boys\nand girls is an interest-bearing account.\nThis is a gift that grows in value from\nyear to year and may become matter of\npride to the young owner who. sees it in\ncrease through his own efforts.', v\nWe have on han